We use the Maximum modulus principle to show that modular forms of non-positive weights are bounded by its value of some element of the upper half plane imaginary part at least 1/2.

> This had a merge-conflict because of #18385. I merged it with the latest master and sorted out the conflicts, ready for review again.

thanks for doing this and again below!

No problem! By the way, I realised while fixing the conflicts that we have two distinct namespaces `ModularGroup` and `UpperHalfPlane.ModularGroup`. Is this deliberate or should they be unified? In any case `denom_one` as presently formulated shouldn't be in the `ModularGroup` namespace, since the `1` is getting elaborated as `1 : ‚Ü•GL(2, ‚Ñù)‚Å∫` rather than as `1 : SL(2, ‚Ñ§)`.

> No problem! By the way, I realised while fixing the conflicts that we have two distinct namespaces `ModularGroup` and `UpperHalfPlane.ModularGroup`. Is this deliberate or should they be unified? In any case `denom_one` as presently formulated shouldn't be in the `ModularGroup` namespace, since the `1` is getting elaborated as `1 : ‚Ü•GL(2, ‚Ñù)‚Å∫` rather than as `1 : SL(2, ‚Ñ§)`.

No that was a mistake. I've removed it now and move `denom_one`.
(I can push fixes with all these changes to your PR, just let me know if that's OK with you.)

> (I can push fixes with all these changes to your PR, just let me know if that's OK with you.)

Oh I was just doing this now. Go ahead and I'll double check there is nothing missing.

I have pushed fixes, I believe everything *outside* the new file `LevelOne` is now OK. I have not looked in detail at the new file, other than fixing knock-on effects of the changes I made elsewhere. Looking at it now.

> I think the results like `modular_S_smul` and those near it should maybe also move down

That doesn't work because it's used in `exists_SL2_smul_eq_of_apply_zero_one_ne_zero` (which is definitely not a `ModularGroup` lemma).
I think the results like `modular_S_smul` and those near it should maybe also move down

```suggestion
/-- For every `œÑ : ‚Ñç` there is some matrix in `SL(2, ‚Ñ§)` that sends it to an element whose
```
and I would either change the second line to "and whose denominator has norm at most 1", or say what \gamma is.
(This could also go in one line, in my opinion.)

```suggestion
/-- The map from `SL(2, ‚Ñ§)` to `Œì(1)`. Its preferable to work with this, since levels of modular
```
what is the alternative to "working with this"? As an outside reader, this comment is not completely clear to me.

How about this?
```suggestion
/-- Every `SlashInvariantForm` `f` satisfies ` f (Œ≥ ‚Ä¢ z) = (denom Œ≥ z) ^ k * f z`. -/

This worries me a bit since `Œì(1)` is by definition a subgroup of `SL(2, ‚Ñ§)`, so there will already be a `Coe` instance going the other way. Do we need it going this way as well? It sounds like it might cause confusion to have Coe instances in both directions at once.
These local notations are getting reused in many places, they should be promoted to `scoped notation` which can be re-opened when needed.

I scoped them in CongruenceSubgroup namespace, ~~but I wanted to try and do it for SlashInvariantForms, but I couldn't seem to do it for SL since the notation was also local (and changing all the notation in the top half of the file seemed to annoying to do). Is there a way to forget the notation halfway down a file?~~
Let me take a look.

I think it would considerably simplify matters to declare this as `(Œ≥ : SL2Z) (hŒ≥ : Œ≥ \in Œì)`. This avoids making `Œì` into a subtype, and so we never have to worry about coercions from this subtype to other things.
It turns out that this notation already exists, scoped in the `MatrixGroups` namespace.

```suggestion
/-- For every `œÑ : ‚Ñç` there is some `Œ≥ ‚àà SL(2, ‚Ñ§)` that sends it to an element whose
imaginary part is at least `1/2` and such that `denom Œ≥ œÑ` has norm at most 1. -/
lemma exists_translate' (œÑ : ‚Ñç) : ‚àÉ Œ≥ : SL(2, ‚Ñ§), 1 / 2 ‚â§ im (Œ≥ ‚Ä¢ œÑ) ‚àß ‚Äñdenom Œ≥ œÑ‚Äñ ‚â§ 1 := by
  by_cases h : 1 / 2 ‚â§ œÑ.im
  ¬∑ exact ‚ü®1, (one_smul SL(2, ‚Ñ§) œÑ).symm ‚ñ∏ h,
      by simp only [ModularGroup.coe_one, denom_one, norm_one, le_refl]‚ü©
  ¬∑ refine (exists_translate œÑ).imp (fun Œ≥ hŒ≥ ‚Ü¶ ‚ü®hŒ≥, ?_‚ü©)
    have h1 : œÑ.im ‚â§ (Œ≥ ‚Ä¢ œÑ).im := by linarith
    rw [ModularGroup.im_smul_eq_div_normSq, le_div_iff‚ÇÄ (normSq_denom_pos (‚ÜëŒ≥) œÑ),
      normSq_eq_norm_sq] at h1
    simpa only [norm_eq_abs, sq_le_one_iff_abs_le_one, Complex.abs_abs] using
      (mul_le_iff_le_one_right œÑ.2).mp h1
```

This is still inside the `UpperHalfPlane` namespace, so the full name of this lemma will still be `UpperHalfPlane.ModularGroup.sl_moeb`; the duplication problem isn't solved.

I suggest collecting all lemmas / defs which take an element of SL(2, Z) as an argument together at the end of the file, so you can close the `UpperHalfPlane` namespace and open the `ModularGroup` namespace. This will also help to make the file more readable, it's a bit confusing as it is now.

The `rfl` at the end of this proof suggests something is amiss; at that point the goal reads as `‚Üëz = ‚Üëz`, where the two arrows (Subtype.val and UpperHalfPlane.coe) are ultimately defeq, but are _not_ syntactically equal, despite printing as the same in the goal view!  I suggest changing the statement to `denom (ModularGroup.S) z = z` instead.
Gamma is not used (probably I overlooked this in my recent refactoring PR).
